					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I should've made a test which polls the PPU status in a loop after the delay to find out exactly how big of a difference there's between the vblanks (should be around 40 CPU cycles in this case), but this time I took the easy way out and just changed the background color. Maybe some other day.</div><br />Yes, please! As it is now, the test doesn't really confirm if there is a missing/non-missing dot. It just tests if the timing is <em>somehow</em> different... ie. it would also trigger on whatever other cases... like 5 extra dots, or 10 missing scanlines, or such stuff.<br /><br />And, just had another idea for RGB PPU detection: Initialize palette memory with some color values. Then enable the &quot;monochrome&quot; mode. On a composite NES, palette reads via Port 2007h will return &quot;color AND 30h&quot; (plus the usual garbage in bit6-7), and according to the &quot;AND 30h&quot;, colors displayed on screen will be <strong>gray, light gray, white</strong> (color 00h,10h,20h/30h).<br />However, judging from Kevin's monochrome RGB palette dumps, the RGB NES would display <strong>black, gray, and white</strong> - quite possible that you can read that values via Port 2007h. Ie. if so, you might get D0h...FFh (RGB.black) instead of 00h (composite.gray), and 00h (RGB.gray) instead of 10h (composite.light gray).<br />I don't have a RGB PPU, and can't test that theory.</div>

